	abstract = {The endocannabinoid system ({ECS}) has emerged as one of the most relevant regulators of energy balance. The {ECS} acts through two cannabinoid receptors: types 1 and 2 ({CB}1 and {CB}2). {CB}1 receptors are widely expressed in the brain, but are also expressed in adipose tissue, skeletal muscle, the liver, the gut, and the pancreas. Blockade of {CB}1 receptors causes a reduction in food intake and a sustained weight loss. This system contributes also to the control of lipid and glucose metabolism, and it is well established that blockade of {CB}1 receptors enhances insulin sensitivity in both humans and rodents. In obese states, endocannabinoid levels are increased and might exert unfavorable effects on insulin-sensitive tissues. This review summarizes the effects of the endocannabinoid system on glucose metabolism in humans and rodents.},
